    "title": "核心塑造",
    "page_range": "4",
    "summary": "This section defines the game design concept of \"核心塑造\" (Core Character Shaping) and outlines its implementation strategy. It can answer questions regarding:\n- **Definition/Topic:** What is \"core shaping\"? A character-centric development strategy designed to establish emotional connections between players and characters.\n- **Procedures/Methods:** What specific elements are utilized to build characters? Integration of character illustrations (立绘), 3D modeling (建模), voice acting (配音), narrative progression (剧情推进), and combat gameplay (战斗玩法).\n- **Claims/Goals:** What is the intended outcome? To foster a strong emotional bond between players and game characters through multi-dimensional character presentation and interactive design.\n- **Entities:** Players, game characters, and development assets (art, models, audio, story, combat systems).\n- **Dates, Tables, Figures, Metrics, Evidence Types:** None mentioned in this section."
  },
  {
    "node_id": "0005",
    "title": "画面风格",
    "page_range": "4",
    "summary": "This section addresses the evolution of visual aesthetics within \"二次元\" (ACG) culture. It can answer retrieval queries regarding:\n- **Topics & Claims:** The historical expansion and shifting boundaries of what constitutes a \"二次元\" visual style.\n- **Entities:** Japanese anime, Korean manhwa, Chinese comics (国漫), players, and the \"二次元\" category.\n- **Definitions:** Defines the \"二次元\" visual style as initially dominated by Japanese anime, but now broadly inclusive of Korean and Chinese comic styles due to cultural development.\n- **Dates/Timeframe:** References an unspecified \"early period\" versus later cultural evolution (no exact dates or years provided).\n- **Procedures, Tables, Figures, Metrics, Evidence Types:** None present; the section offers a qualitative cultural claim without step-by-step procedures, quantitative metrics, visual aids, or cited evidence.\n- **Retrievable Questions:** What was the dominant early visual style for 二次元? How has the recognized visual style for 二次元 changed over time? Which non-Japanese comic styles are now accepted by players as part of the 二次元 aesthetic?"
  },
